title: For Sale/Trade:  PVS-14 Gen 3 Autogated Night Vision Monocular w/ accessories
postcontent: This is a PVS-14 Gen 3 night vision monocular in lightly used condition. As you can see from the picture, it produces an exceptionally clear image with virtually no spots or blemishes, meaning it was probably hand selected for tube quality (it is within specs for even a new $3600 unit to have a few black spots around the edge of the image, which this one doesn't have). For reference, the neighbors' house in the pic is about 60-80 yards away. The dark pic is what the same scene looks like to the naked eye.This unit appears to be autogated -- it dims when pointed at a bright light, which prevents tube damage. This unit comes with a dual battery housing, which gives it a longer battery life than the single battery units (65 hours continual use as opposed to 40 hours). It takes AA batteries.I was told by the previous owner that this unit has only been used for a few hours... the condition of the unit and quality of the image is definitely consistent with that. I have used it less than an hour myself, so it has the vast majority of its service life left, and will provide many good years of service.I was also told by the previous owner that this unit has an Omni tube, meaning it is mil spec and that unlike the ITT/Pinnacle tubes, it is rated for .308 recoil.It comes with the pictured accessories, which include the attached lens cover/pinhole lens (for testing the unit in regular lighting), a J-arm mount (used for mounting to a helmet or "skull crusher" headgear), as well as a weapon mount, for mounting the unit on a Picatinny rail either behind or in front of AR-height optics. It works great behind my Aimpoint PRO or Comp M4. It also works great in front of a scope that can adjust down to 1x.Get this very clean Gen 3 night vision unit in great condition for over $1,000 less than a new one would cost, or for the same as you would pay for a Gen 2 unit, if you want to think of it that way. If you have never used Gen 3 night vision, let's just say it blows Gen 1 and Gen 2 out of the water in every possible way... it's not even close. A unit like this gives you a massively unfair advantage in any low light situation.I would take $2500 OBO, and would be willing to take a partial trade for the following items:Good long range precision glass, spotting scope with mil reticle, plates, plate carrier, soft armor.I am willing to ship, with the buyer paying.If you can meet me near the Oklahoma City area, I'd be glad to meet you after dark and let you see what this unit is really capable of. You won't be disappointed.I am listing this on other forums/marketplaces, and expect a quick sale. First one to reply agreeing to buy takes it. Email me through this site or text 4o5 88o o5o6.

postcontent: Walther PP 32 Auto**LAYAWAY AVAILABLE** Condition Used minor wear and tear one mag Price $1495.00**Harvey Special** Inventory # G-19716-1 Manufacturer Walther Model PP Caliber 32 Auto Firearm Type Pistol Barrel 3.8in Fun Fact  The Walther PP (Polizeipistole, or police pistol) series pistols are blowback-operated semi-automatic pistols, developed by the German arms manufacturer Walther.[2] It features an exposed hammer, a traditional double-action trigger mechanism,[3] a single-column magazine, and a fixed barrel that also acts as the guide rod for the recoil spring. The series includes the Walther PP, PPK, PPK/S, and PPK/E. Various PP series are manufactured in either Germany, France or the United States.[4] Since 2002, the PPK variant is solely manufactured by Smith & Wesson in Houlton, Maine, United States, under license from Carl Walther GmbH Sportwaffen. In the past, this particular model has been manufactured by Carl Walther in its own factory in Germany, as well as under licenses by Manurhin in Alsace, France, and by Interarms in Alexandria, Virginia, US. The PP and the PPK were among the world's first successful double action semi-automatic pistols and were widely copied, but are still made by Walther. The design inspired other pistols, among them the Soviet Makarov, the Hungarian FEG PA-63, and the Argentinian Bersa Thunder 380. The PP and PPK were both popular with European police and civilians, for being reliable and concealable. During World War II, they were issued to the German military, including the Luftwaffe, as well as the police.

Always ready to revolutionize the arms industry, Bushmaster returns with their new Carbon 15 line. The Carbon 15 line of rifles and carbines each feature a lightweight receiver constructed from carbon composite, which provides for a product that is 40 percent lighter than comparable firearms with aluminum receivers. This particular model joins the ORC line, which is their new "optics-ready carbine," a line of carbines that ship with optic riser mounts ready for your preferred optic. In some cases, ORC carbines even ship with included optics. Such is the case with the Bushmaster Carbon 15 ORC, which ships with a Bushnell red dot sight that will offer precision targeting during all styles of shooting.
As noted, the Bushmaster Carbon 15 ORC features a 16-inch barrel alongside an overall length of 32 1/2 inches, which can be reduced by four inches via the telescoping stock. Both the 4150 chrome-moly steel barrel (1:9 inch twist rate) and the chamber feature a hard chrome lining, which serves to protect both components from rust and corrosion as well as give them higher resistance to wear and an extended service life. Also included is the aforementioned synthetic six-position telescoping stock. When combined with the light weight of the upper & carbon composite lower receiver,  you get a carbine that weighs in at just 5 1/2 pounds. Additionally, each carbine boasts a heavy oval M4-type handguard. And though the ORC carbine does not include iron sights, it does include a receiver-length Picatinny rail with two 1 1/4 inch optic riser blocks as well as a Bushnell red dot sight. As noted, the Carbon 15 ORC is chambered in 5.56x45mm NATO/.223 Remington and includes a single 30-round magazine.

title: For Sale/Trade:  MLE MAS 1874, Commissioned officer's 1873
postcontent: This is an MLE MAS St.Etienne 1874. This was the sidearm carried by officers in the French army. There were two identical models, the 1873 was not blued, and was made for non commissioned officers and had a total production of around 300,000 total. The 1874, pictured here, was far more rare. It was blued, which quite a good bit of the original bluing remains. The 1874 was given to commissioned officers only. It had a total production of only about 27,000, making it very rare today. This particular one was made in 1879. That's right, 147 years ago. Recently, a 1874 in similar in condition sold on an auction site for $1275.00 One sold a couple months before that for $1320.00. In France they sell for about 1600 Euro, which is closer to $1900 US. I am looking to trade this for a good running decent looking spare vehicle.  I would also consider trades for more modern firearms.I am willing to ship from my FFL to yours anywhere in the US.
